00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:29,990
into whether production systems are
not just up, but correct and running.

244
00:15:30,490 --> 00:15:32,920
Draw this together into a single frame.

245
00:15:33,130 --> 00:15:38,080
Reliability in a regulated enterprise
systems is not a single layer property.

246
00:15:38,320 --> 00:15:41,980
It has three layers, and most
engineering teams are only covering

247
00:15:41,980 --> 00:15:46,360
the first one, which is infrastructure
monitoring, like uptime, error

248
00:15:46,360 --> 00:15:48,970
rates, latency, resource utilization.

249
00:15:49,609 --> 00:15:50,810
And things like this.

250
00:15:50,899 --> 00:15:54,829
This is the layer which is necessary,
which is non-negotiable, but it is

251
00:15:54,829 --> 00:15:58,789
not sufficient because it cannot
tell you whether the decisions

252
00:15:58,789 --> 00:16:00,469
your system is making are correct.

253
00:16:01,060 --> 00:16:05,349
Next one is workflow reliability,
like decision accuracy rates,

254
00:16:05,409 --> 00:16:09,099
rule execution, validity,
output, distribution, monitoring.

255
00:16:09,339 --> 00:16:12,579
This is the layer most
SRE teams do not have.

256
00:16:12,609 --> 00:16:16,689
It is also the layer that determines
whether your system is running

257
00:16:17,139 --> 00:16:21,159
and doing its actual job, not just
running, but running correctly.

258
00:16:21,785 --> 00:16:26,884
S. And the final one is competence
validation, like audit trial integrity,

259
00:16:26,884 --> 00:16:31,204
regulatory field completeness,
verified automated outcomes.

260
00:16:31,564 --> 00:16:35,344
This is a layer that regulators
examine when it fails.

261
00:16:35,344 --> 00:16:37,894
The consequences are
financial and reputational.

262
00:16:38,170 --> 00:16:42,790
So the final sentence on this slide
becomes the true definition of

263
00:16:42,790 --> 00:16:44,619
reliability in this environment.

264
00:16:44,920 --> 00:16:49,420
Reliability in regulated enterprise
systems means ensuring automated

265
00:16:49,420 --> 00:16:51,460
decisions remain correct.

266
00:16:51,700 --> 00:16:53,530
T and auditable.

267
00:16:53,800 --> 00:16:59,230
That is the, that is broader than uptime
and latency, and that is the reliability

268
00:16:59,230 --> 00:17:01,900
as the business actually experiences it.

269
00:17:02,400 --> 00:17:06,210
So as I close, I want to leave
you with one simple idea.

270
00:17:06,510 --> 00:17:08,610
A system can be up and still be wrong.

271
00:17:08,760 --> 00:17:13,620
It can meet latency targets, show
low error rates, and keep every

272
00:17:13,860 --> 00:17:17,250
infrastructure dashboard green
while still producing incorrect

273
00:17:17,250 --> 00:17:21,090
decisions, skipping comprehensive
checks, or creating gaps in order.

274
00:17:21,590 --> 00:17:24,950
And in regulated systems,
those are not minor issues.

275
00:17:24,950 --> 00:17:26,540
Those are reliability issues.

276
00:17:26,780 --> 00:17:32,870
So if we want stronger production systems,
we need to extend our thinking for sure.

277
00:17:32,930 --> 00:17:35,960
From testing before release
to validation in production.

278
00:17:36,360 --> 00:17:41,130
From infrastructure health to workflow
correctness, from uptime alone to

279
00:17:41,130 --> 00:17:46,170
decisions that are correct T and
auditable, that is how we strengthen

280
00:17:46,200 --> 00:17:48,390
our regulated production systems.

281
00:17:48,660 --> 00:17:50,130
Thank you so much for your time.

282
00:17:50,130 --> 00:17:52,020
I hope this has been very useful.

283
00:17:52,050 --> 00:17:55,440
I would welcome the opportunity to
discuss any of this ideas further.

284
00:17:55,860 --> 00:17:56,340
Goodbye.

